@countmcnuggula Important to note that reagent test kits are not necessarily easy to use without training, and none of them offer a 100% guarantee of accuracy. It’s also v easy to miss a color change in the early stages of the reaction & for some reactions to be overshadowed by others
•grow lights are cheaper than you think!! although more expensive ones are probably higher quality, they help a lot and are easy to find online!

•typically, variegated plants (white patches or stripes of missing chlorophyll or whatever) require higher levels of light than their non-variegated counterparts (because the absence of chlorophyll lessens the leaf’s ability to absorb light)

•don’t use ice cold water because it can shock your plant, room temperature is ideal 
•just because a plant will tolerate low light that doesn’t mean it will thrive in low light, those plants often grow better with higher light levels too

•yellow leaves either mean over or underwatering. Good luck figuring out which lmao
•buy a moisture metre/probe!!! They are cheap and will tell you how moist the soil is without you having to guess if deeper soil has dried or not

•if your plant is getting “legs” meaning if it seems to be getting especially stemmy and the leaves are becoming quite spread apart where they were compact before, this means your plant needs more light!

•plants don’t like still air, a small air purifier or nearby fan helps keep things circulating and discourages mould :-)
•clustering plants near to each other helps retain a little humidity because plants respirate and “breathe out” water thru their leaves

... waste water from a freshwater aquarium (no aquarium salts) this is v nutritive for your plants as well as dechlorinated 
•sprinkling a pinch or two of cinnamon on top of the soil discourages fungus growth, which means no food for pests like fungus gnats, plus it smells güd

•plants don’t like the chlorine that comes in tap water, and distilled water lacks nutrients. I like to use a dechlorinator that I buy at the pet store. i use a product called reptisafe that neutralizes chlorine and adds trace nutrients
